we'll have some time for questions.

33
00:01:28,570 --> 00:01:30,851
So, what is Keyforge?

34
00:01:31,931 --> 00:01:34,192
Well, Keyforge is, as you saw in the talk's title,

35
00:01:34,692 --> 00:01:36,033
the world's first unique deck game.

36
00:01:36,513 --> 00:01:38,974
It's designed by legendary game designer Richard Garfield,

37
00:01:39,414 --> 00:01:41,634
of Magic the Gathering, Netrunner,

38
00:01:41,995 --> 00:01:43,255
and recently Artifact fame.

39
00:01:45,095 --> 00:01:47,916
It's very different than a traditional TCG

40
00:01:49,017 --> 00:01:49,897
in the following ways.

41
00:01:50,977 --> 00:01:53,758
So, you know, two decks have the exact same composition.

42
00:01:55,079 --> 00:01:56,599
Each and every deck has a unique name.

43
00:01:57,407 --> 00:01:59,347
Each and every deck has a unique card back,

44
00:02:00,028 --> 00:02:01,388
and decks are not customizable.

45
00:02:02,169 --> 00:02:05,410
These set it apart and make it a really weird thing,

46
00:02:06,130 --> 00:02:10,252
but how exactly do we wanna make a game like this?

47
00:02:11,392 --> 00:02:14,614
We started Key Forge with a really distinct philosophy,

48
00:02:15,734 --> 00:02:19,335
and I think it's best put in a quote by Richard Garfield

49
00:02:19,876 --> 00:02:20,736
that we had in the rule book.

50
00:02:22,057 --> 00:02:22,857
I've always been attached

51
00:02:22,877 --> 00:02:24,578
to good procedurally generated content.

52
00:02:25,369 --> 00:02:29,192
Game worlds generated in this way really feel as though they belong to me, the player.

53
00:02:30,373 --> 00:02:32,795
I am often discovering them as I play.

54
00:02:33,076 --> 00:02:34,897
The designer didn't even know they existed.

55
00:02:35,678 --> 00:02:39,061
Often games with such content are extremely managed experiences.

56
00:02:39,822 --> 00:02:43,185
Everyone goes through the same storylines and can experience the same gameplay by making

57
00:02:43,205 --> 00:02:43,986
the same decisions.

58
00:02:44,807 --> 00:02:46,348
Everything they experience feels planned.

59
00:02:46,928 --> 00:02:50,191
The contrast feels to me like the difference between exploring a jungle and walking in

60
00:02:50,212 --> 00:02:50,892
an amusement park.

61
00:02:52,109 --> 00:02:55,630
Now what he meant by this is when you go to an amusement park, when you go to Disney World,

62
00:02:56,351 --> 00:02:57,871
you know where all the rides are.

63
00:02:58,091 --> 00:03:01,832
You get a map right at the beginning, you know where to get on the roller coaster, where

64
00:03:01,852 --> 00:03:05,114
to do the tilt-a-whirl, where to get your cotton candy, and where to go to the bathroom.

65
00:03:06,154 --> 00:03:09,395
And you know the kind of fun that you're going to have on all those things.

66
00:03:09,435 --> 00:03:12,056
You know how you like roller coasters, you know how you like the tilt-a-whirl.

67
00:03:14,043 --> 00:03:16,025
You walk through the jungle, you go on a safari,

68
00:03:16,425 --> 00:03:18,846
you're going down a trail and you're not quite sure

69
00:03:18,866 --> 00:03:19,547
what you're gonna see.

70
00:03:20,007 --> 00:03:21,528
You're not sure what you're gonna experience,

71
00:03:22,068 --> 00:03:23,609
but you know it's gonna be uniquely yours.

72
00:03:23,829 --> 00:03:26,671
You could walk down that same trail a thousand times

73
00:03:27,251 --> 00:03:29,133
and each and every time you would see different things.

74
00:03:29,193 --> 00:03:30,774
You would have a different experience.

75
00:03:31,574 --> 00:03:33,655
Richard really wanted to take that concept

76
00:03:33,775 --> 00:03:35,336
and capture it in a game.

77
00:03:35,937 --> 00:03:37,698
One where no matter what happened,

78
00:03:37,758 --> 00:03:39,339
you weren't going to run into the same decks

79
00:03:39,379 --> 00:03:40,079
week after week.

80
00:03:40,460 --> 00:03:42,161
You weren't going to have the same matchups

81
00:03:42,181 --> 00:03:42,861
week after week.

82
00:03:43,401 --> 00:03:43,701
You weren't.

83
00:03:44,345 --> 00:03:46,585
He's gonna know what you were going to run into every week.

84
00:03:47,566 --> 00:03:50,207
And so that's where his impetus for Keyforge came from.

85
00:03:51,467 --> 00:03:53,868
So, what makes Keyforge unique?

86
00:03:55,148 --> 00:03:57,009
Each and every deck is an archon.

87
00:03:57,749 --> 00:04:00,130
Now, our archon is our player insert.

88
00:04:00,970 --> 00:04:03,451
It's the way you interact with the game world,

89
00:04:03,791 --> 00:04:05,312
and it's representative of your deck.

90
00:04:06,052 --> 00:04:08,213
That character is made of a combination

91
00:04:08,253 --> 00:04:11,734
between a unique card back and a unique name.

92
00:04:12,542 --> 00:04:14,343
Now again, each and every one of these

93
00:04:14,683 --> 00:04:16,764
completely distinct throughout the entire world.

94
00:04:19,106 --> 00:04:23,948
Now, each deck is made out of 37 cards.

95
00:04:23,988 --> 00:04:26,430
12 of those cards are from three different houses,

96
00:04:26,590 --> 00:04:29,872
the game's factions, and the last is an Archon card

97
00:04:29,932 --> 00:04:33,154
representing your character, and on the back of it,

98
00:04:33,594 --> 00:04:36,376
showing the deck list, all the cards that are in your deck

99
00:04:36,576 --> 00:04:37,236
and their rarities.

100
00:04:38,492 --> 00:04:40,934
Now that deck consists of action cards, artifacts,

101
00:04:41,014 --> 00:04:43,315
creatures, and upgrades, just to show you guys

102
00:04:43,716 --> 00:04:45,637
the kinds of variety we have in there.

103
00:04:47,218 --> 00:04:49,820
Now, Key Forge is played very differently

104
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:52,061
than many other TCGs.

105
00:04:52,942 --> 00:04:56,484
Oftentimes those games devolve into a attempt

106
00:04:56,504 --> 00:04:58,405
to beat the other player in the face, if you will.

107
00:04:59,286 --> 00:05:02,128
Whereas Key Forge is you're trying

108
00:05:02,148 --> 00:05:03,308
to beat your opponent to the punch.

109
00:05:04,132 --> 00:05:05,192
It's a race to the finish.

110
00:05:05,992 --> 00:05:08,694
And players will do that by collecting a resource,

111
00:05:09,314 --> 00:05:11,235
or a victory point, called amber.

112
00:05:12,315 --> 00:05:14,396
Now, players will collect amber throughout the game

113
00:05:14,436 --> 00:05:15,356
by doing various things.

114
00:05:15,396 --> 00:05:17,577
This includes using their creatures,

115
00:05:18,538 --> 00:05:21,499
playing cards, and a whole host of other ways.

116
00:05:22,139 --> 00:05:24,400
But, as players collect amber,

117
00:05:25,481 --> 00:05:27,822
if they start their turn with six of them,

118
00:05:28,582 --> 00:05:30,163
they will spend them and forge a key.

119
00:05:31,963 --> 00:05:34,826
The first player to forge three keys wins the game.

120
00:05:36,508 --> 00:05:39,191
However, there's a unique twist to Keyforge,

121
00:05:39,271 --> 00:05:41,814
and that is that it doesn't have a resource.

122
00:05:42,615 --> 00:05:45,438
Like many other games that have a mana or credits

123
00:05:45,558 --> 00:05:48,421
or any sort of point you spend to play cards,

124
00:05:49,142 --> 00:05:51,104
in Keyforge, you're instead going to choose

125
00:05:51,404 --> 00:05:52,886
one active house each turn.

126
00:05:53,542 --> 00:05:57,004
I told you earlier that each deck consists of 12 cards

127
00:05:57,044 --> 00:05:58,085
of three different houses,

128
00:05:58,806 --> 00:06:00,527
which means that you're roughly activating

129
00:06:01,028 --> 00:06:02,949
one third of your deck every turn.

130
00:06:04,630 --> 00:06:06,812
When you have a house as your active house,

131
00:06:06,972 --> 00:06:08,534
you're gonna be able to play cards at that house,

132
00:06:09,054 --> 00:06:11,576
use cards in play, and discard cards.

133
00:06:12,096 --> 00:06:14,518
So you need to really be careful how you're managing

134
00:06:14,618 --> 00:06:17,781
both the cards that are in your hand and in play,

135
00:06:17,961 --> 00:06:19,602
so you can have the maximum amount of effect

136
00:06:19,662 --> 00:06:20,403
on the game space.

137
00:06:22,345 --> 00:06:22,465
Now.

138
00:06:22,959 --> 00:06:25,460
let's talk a little bit about the flavor of the Crucible.

139
00:06:25,780 --> 00:06:26,640
Excuse me, Kiefforge.

140
00:06:27,660 --> 00:06:30,301
So, Kiefforge takes place on a world called the Crucible.

141
00:06:31,521 --> 00:06:33,922
It's an artificial planet in the center of the universe,

142
00:06:34,022 --> 00:06:36,803
and it's made by some mysterious beings

143
00:06:36,843 --> 00:06:38,863
that people don't really know that much about

144
00:06:38,923 --> 00:06:39,503
on the Crucible.

145
00:06:39,603 --> 00:06:40,664
They're called the Architects.

146
00:06:41,264 --> 00:06:42,844
At least, that's what everyone calls them.

147
00:06:43,984 --> 00:06:45,525
And, the only native inhabitants

148
00:06:45,925 --> 00:06:47,385
of the Crucible are the Archons.

149
00:06:48,376 --> 00:06:53,797
They show up mysteriously and do various deeds across the land and earn their names that

150
00:06:53,837 --> 00:06:53,997
way.

151
00:06:54,778 --> 00:06:57,238
The other native thing to the crucible is amber.

152
00:06:57,458 --> 00:07:03,180
As we previously talked about, it grows pretty much everywhere and is a psychoreactive substance,

153
00:07:03,640 --> 00:07:07,921
meaning that it responds to the hopes, dreams, and thoughts of the people that hold it or

154
00:07:07,981 --> 00:07:08,541
try to use it.

155
00:07:10,461 --> 00:07:12,722
Of course, the Crucible being an artificial planet,

156
00:07:13,303 --> 00:07:16,825
it is made of the pieces of hundreds of thousands

157
00:07:16,865 --> 00:07:18,786
of different worlds from across the universe.

158
00:07:19,667 --> 00:07:21,968
Now, that means when you take a piece of the world,

159
00:07:22,669 --> 00:07:24,890
put it on the Crucible, it means that all the wildlife,

160
00:07:24,970 --> 00:07:27,472
all the people, all the different things come with it,

161
00:07:27,932 --> 00:07:29,893
merging together and bringing countless

162
00:07:29,953 --> 00:07:31,014
alien cultures together.

163
00:07:31,034 --> 00:07:34,556
Now those cultures work together to try and survive

164
00:07:34,596 --> 00:07:36,217
such a weird and strange world.

165
00:07:36,237 --> 00:07:39,239
And let's talk a little bit about those cultures.

166
00:07:40,382 --> 00:07:41,882
First of which is the Bravnar,

167
00:07:42,763 --> 00:07:44,803
which are our Viking techno-barbarians.

168
00:07:45,564 --> 00:07:47,605
They're full of giants and goblins,

169
00:07:47,685 --> 00:07:51,246
and they believe that the strongest are the most right,

170
00:07:51,486 --> 00:07:52,167
the most correct,

171
00:07:52,707 --> 00:07:54,087
and so that's how they live their society.

172
00:07:55,188 --> 00:07:58,069
Now, mechanically, that means they focus on fighting.

173
00:07:58,849 --> 00:08:00,530
They love getting in a good scrap,

174
00:08:01,490 --> 00:08:03,371
and they have the powerful creatures

175
00:08:03,931 --> 00:08:05,432
that they need to back it up.

176
00:08:06,484 --> 00:08:08,905
They also have lots of abilities to deal direct damage.

177
00:08:08,925 --> 00:08:10,646
You know, just playing a card

178
00:08:10,666 --> 00:08:12,407
and dealing three damage to something.

179
00:08:13,767 --> 00:08:16,689
The Deice are bizarre demons and imps

180
00:08:16,749 --> 00:08:18,410
that live below the surface of the crucible.

181
00:08:19,610 --> 00:08:23,012
And they are entirely incapable of emotion themselves,

182
00:08:23,232 --> 00:08:26,113
so they need to steal the emotions of others

183
00:08:26,173 --> 00:08:27,274
by capturing an enabler.

184
00:08:28,514 --> 00:08:31,195
Now their mechanics focus on board control,

185
00:08:31,536 --> 00:08:33,156
hand manipulation, and parrying effects,

186
00:08:33,677 --> 00:08:36,038
making them kind of our catch-all control faction.

187
00:08:38,955 --> 00:08:41,156
The Logos, my personal favorite,

188
00:08:41,716 --> 00:08:43,858
are the mad scientists of the Crucible.

189
00:08:44,598 --> 00:08:47,880
They tinker and experiment constantly

190
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:51,362
and have kind of forgotten what their previous bodies

191
00:08:51,402 --> 00:08:53,904
looked like as they've modified themselves with cybernetics.

192
00:08:54,684 --> 00:08:57,105
They're very much science for the sake of science,

193
00:08:57,185 --> 00:08:59,827
asking can they rather than should they.

194
00:09:01,628 --> 00:09:02,128
Mechanically.

195
00:09:02,799 --> 00:09:06,001
They focus on hand management, drawing cards,

196
00:09:06,121 --> 00:09:07,522
putting cards aside for later,

197
00:09:08,022 --> 00:09:11,024
discarding cards from their hand to improve their draw,

198
00:09:11,845 --> 00:09:14,367
and cross-faction play, letting them continue

199
00:09:14,407 --> 00:09:16,448
to manage that hand and the board state.

200
00:09:16,908 --> 00:09:19,030
They also have more artifacts than any other faction,

201
00:09:19,070 --> 00:09:21,071
which makes sense for all the gizmos

202
00:09:21,131 --> 00:09:22,692
and gadgets they're always creating.

203
00:09:24,133 --> 00:09:26,695
Next, a little closer to home, is Mars.

204
00:09:28,047 --> 00:09:30,570
which literally classic sci-fi Martians.

205
00:09:31,050 --> 00:09:32,772
They live in a two-tiered society

206
00:09:33,012 --> 00:09:36,576
with the taller Martians being in control

207
00:09:36,596 --> 00:09:37,336
of the shorter ones,

208
00:09:37,396 --> 00:09:39,258
and I don't know where that idea came from.

209
00:09:40,680 --> 00:09:42,682
But they're very, very xenophobic.

210
00:09:42,722 --> 00:09:45,705
They don't, at least the taller ones are,

211
00:09:45,745 --> 00:09:48,207
and they don't get along as well

212
00:09:48,247 --> 00:09:49,508
with everyone else on the crucible.

213
00:09:50,680 --> 00:09:52,460
Now this is reflected in their mechanics

214
00:09:52,920 --> 00:09:54,760
in that they're very self-synergistic.

215
00:09:55,401 --> 00:09:57,041
They work very well with themselves,

216
00:09:57,121 --> 00:09:58,901
but not with other factions.

217
00:09:59,821 --> 00:10:01,602
They also have powerful abduction effects,

218
00:10:01,682 --> 00:10:04,262
causing your opponent to capture their own amber,

219
00:10:04,662 --> 00:10:07,103
so when you destroy their creatures, you get it instead.

220
00:10:08,063 --> 00:10:09,963
In addition to that, they have key defense effects,

221
00:10:10,323 --> 00:10:12,103
increasing the cost of your opponent's keys,

222
00:10:12,624 --> 00:10:14,544
so they have to gather more and more amber

223
00:10:14,584 --> 00:10:15,904
in order to be able to beat you.

224
00:10:18,545 --> 00:10:18,985
The Sanctum.

225
00:10:19,958 --> 00:10:23,139
a religious order of knights and spirits.

226
00:10:23,659 --> 00:10:26,400
They live on floating cities throughout the crucible

227
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:30,521
and try and maintain law and order the best they can.

228
00:10:31,521 --> 00:10:33,361
And they're on a quest for enlightenment,

229
00:10:33,742 --> 00:10:36,542
trying to figure out exactly why they're here

230
00:10:36,562 --> 00:10:39,883
on the crucible and gain transcendence from it.

231
00:10:41,484 --> 00:10:44,304
Mechanically, they're very defense-focused.

232
00:10:44,805 --> 00:10:47,425
They have more armor in their faction than any other.

233
00:10:48,024 --> 00:10:50,407
and armor allows them to shrug off damage.

234
00:10:51,289 --> 00:10:54,493
They also, to benefit that, have a lot of healing,

235
00:10:54,573 --> 00:10:56,075
so if you do manage to damage them,

236
00:10:56,556 --> 00:10:58,438
they have the capability to heal that right up.

237
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:01,723
They'll also prevent their opponent

238
00:11:01,763 --> 00:11:04,407
from being able to forge keys by taking their amber away

239
00:11:04,447 --> 00:11:05,708
and holding onto it for a bit.

240
00:11:08,234 --> 00:11:12,377
The Shadows is a sneaky society of thieves full of dark elves,

241
00:11:12,738 --> 00:11:14,959
and they love, love amassing treasure.

242
00:11:15,019 --> 00:11:16,240
They can't get enough of it.

243
00:11:16,761 --> 00:11:19,723
And more just the physical act of taking it and hoarding it

244
00:11:19,783 --> 00:11:22,385
rather than exactly what that treasure is.

245
00:11:23,386 --> 00:11:26,808
So after coming to the Crucible, they fell in love with Amber.

246
00:11:29,797 --> 00:11:31,798
Now, mechanically, it makes sense.

247
00:11:31,838 --> 00:11:32,879
They have amber control.

248
00:11:32,899 --> 00:11:35,060
They are the best faction at stealing amber

249
00:11:35,080 --> 00:11:38,462
from their opponent, which is an extremely effective way

250
00:11:38,942 --> 00:11:40,423
of gaining it yourself.

251
00:11:41,723 --> 00:11:42,544
And also hard to hit.

252
00:11:42,824 --> 00:11:44,605
They have a lot of the keyword elusive,

253
00:11:45,165 --> 00:11:46,806
which means that your opponent will have to spend

254
00:11:46,866 --> 00:11:48,707
two creatures for every one they attack.

255
00:11:49,867 --> 00:11:51,068
And they get some pinging damage

256
00:11:51,148 --> 00:11:52,328
for harrying their opponent,

257
00:11:52,449 --> 00:11:53,789
doing a point of damage here and there

