275
00:12:41,324 --> 00:12:43,385
So what challenges did we face during the development

276
00:12:43,405 --> 00:12:43,905
of this game?

277
00:12:45,146 --> 00:12:46,727
So I'm going to talk to you about three

278
00:12:46,767 --> 00:12:47,988
different categories of challenges

279
00:12:48,028 --> 00:12:49,909
today, the first of which being mechanical.

280
00:12:50,911 --> 00:12:53,091
Next, we'll talk about the testing we did,

281
00:12:53,852 --> 00:12:55,952
and then we'll talk about the user experience,

282
00:12:56,032 --> 00:12:57,812
how we made this game work

283
00:12:58,532 --> 00:13:00,573
with such a strange and different concept.

284
00:13:02,613 --> 00:13:03,914
So, mechanical.

285
00:13:04,834 --> 00:13:06,334
What types of challenges did we face?

286
00:13:07,834 --> 00:13:10,135
We had to figure out how we were gonna make decks

287
00:13:10,595 --> 00:13:11,775
that were entirely unique,

288
00:13:12,275 --> 00:13:13,415
how we were gonna ensure

289
00:13:13,756 --> 00:13:15,316
that those decks were entirely unique,

290
00:13:16,076 --> 00:13:17,416
how we were gonna figure out

291
00:13:17,456 --> 00:13:18,977
how each of these decks was gonna be named.

292
00:13:19,872 --> 00:13:22,153
and how we were gonna, how the heck we were gonna

293
00:13:22,193 --> 00:13:24,215
possibly make card backs unique

294
00:13:24,255 --> 00:13:25,556
for every single deck out there.

295
00:13:27,918 --> 00:13:29,679
So, how does a deck mean?

296
00:13:30,980 --> 00:13:33,642
We have the almighty algorithm to thank for that.

297
00:13:34,582 --> 00:13:39,246
The algorithm is a collection of tons of different rules,

298
00:13:39,886 --> 00:13:44,429
regulations, and restrictions that cause a deck to, whoa,

299
00:13:45,899 --> 00:13:47,239
be in the form that we desire.

300
00:13:48,540 --> 00:13:50,960
When a deck, when we hit the button to make a deck,

301
00:13:51,340 --> 00:13:52,620
the first thing the algorithm does

302
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:54,041
is collect all those rules.

303
00:13:54,961 --> 00:13:57,381
Gets them together, some of these are as simple as like,

304
00:13:57,921 --> 00:14:01,442
there's 37 cards in the deck, and one Archon card.

305
00:14:01,802 --> 00:14:04,243
There's three houses, those sort of things.

306
00:14:04,283 --> 00:14:06,603
Basic stuff all the way up to very, very,

307
00:14:07,403 --> 00:14:10,004
very interesting stuff I wish I could tell you more about.

308
00:14:10,124 --> 00:14:15,445
But, the next step is it's gonna choose houses for that deck.

309
00:14:17,362 --> 00:14:20,605
And this is important because those houses

310
00:14:20,665 --> 00:14:22,727
are gonna dictate all the other choices

311
00:14:22,847 --> 00:14:25,189
that the algorithm is making when it's building a deck.

312
00:14:26,490 --> 00:14:28,672
Then it's gonna start to generate some cards.

313
00:14:30,393 --> 00:14:31,734
And it goes one faction at a time,

314
00:14:32,535 --> 00:14:35,597
filling in the deck list with all of the different cards

315
00:14:36,318 --> 00:14:37,959
that can possibly be in it.

316
00:14:39,060 --> 00:14:42,303
Now, when it's doing that, each time it's generating a card

317
00:14:42,803 --> 00:14:44,445
it's making a rarity calculation

318
00:14:44,865 --> 00:14:46,306
when it's rolling that card individually.

319
00:14:47,312 --> 00:14:50,035
Then it's looking if there's any variance of that card.

320
00:14:50,796 --> 00:14:53,899
Now this would be example that some cards in Key Forge

321
00:14:53,939 --> 00:14:55,621
have more than one version of that card.

322
00:14:56,583 --> 00:14:59,726
Master of one, two, and three is a perfect example.

323
00:14:59,766 --> 00:15:02,750
It's a card that all of the numerical values on the card

324
00:15:02,890 --> 00:15:04,352
change for each different version.

325
00:15:04,852 --> 00:15:06,334
And you never know which one you're gonna get.

326
00:15:07,215 --> 00:15:07,335
Now.

327
00:15:08,014 --> 00:15:09,614
There's also some companion cards,

328
00:15:10,215 --> 00:15:12,956
a card that always comes with a different card.

329
00:15:13,456 --> 00:15:14,837
And if you look under the logos,

330
00:15:14,857 --> 00:15:15,757
the center section there,

331
00:15:15,777 --> 00:15:17,918
you can see that there is a time traveler

332
00:15:18,018 --> 00:15:19,279
and help from future self there.

333
00:15:20,460 --> 00:15:22,541
Now, those cards always come together.

334
00:15:23,161 --> 00:15:24,341
You never see them separate.

335
00:15:24,642 --> 00:15:26,823
And they have a strong synergy with one another

336
00:15:26,963 --> 00:15:27,723
and interact well.

337
00:15:30,284 --> 00:15:31,945
Now, brace yourselves.

338
00:15:33,065 --> 00:15:33,786
We got a math alert.

339
00:15:35,250 --> 00:15:36,751
So if you have a weak constitution,

340
00:15:36,791 --> 00:15:38,032
I'd recommend leaving the room now.

341
00:15:38,052 --> 00:15:42,074
Because we're going to talk about ensuring uniqueness.

342
00:15:43,675 --> 00:15:46,236
Now, to do this, we're first going to talk

343
00:15:46,256 --> 00:15:48,858
about the maximum number of decks.

344
00:15:48,898 --> 00:15:52,339
There's 369 non-fixed cards in Keyforge,

345
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:53,840
and 36 card per deck.

346
00:15:54,621 --> 00:15:55,821
Which means we can take 369 to the 36th power,

347
00:15:55,841 --> 00:15:57,282
which gives us 259 Novemvignantelian decks.

348
00:16:04,643 --> 00:16:09,687
Now, big number, but most of these decks ignore our rules.

349
00:16:10,688 --> 00:16:12,690
They're just an abstract possibility.

350
00:16:13,070 --> 00:16:15,012
We have cards that are divided by house,

351
00:16:16,032 --> 00:16:17,574
we have cards that are different rarities,

352
00:16:18,294 --> 00:16:20,416
and we have a ton of other rules that dictate

353
00:16:20,476 --> 00:16:22,778
exactly what cards can possibly go into a deck.

354
00:16:23,879 --> 00:16:26,120
Now, if we take all of those into consideration,

355
00:16:26,501 --> 00:16:29,343
we get a much, much more reasonable 104 octillion decks.

356
00:16:31,775 --> 00:16:33,716
which is still enough for each person on the planet

357
00:16:33,756 --> 00:16:36,338
to have billions and billions of decks unique to them.

358
00:16:38,679 --> 00:16:41,461
But how do we solve this?

359
00:16:42,141 --> 00:16:46,023
We actually have a really interesting mathematical problem

360
00:16:46,203 --> 00:16:47,144
called the birthday problem,

361
00:16:47,484 --> 00:16:50,445
and that states that if you get a group of people together,

362
00:16:50,826 --> 00:16:51,986
such as we are here today,

363
00:16:52,727 --> 00:16:55,328
that the possibility that they have a shared birthday

364
00:16:55,388 --> 00:16:58,189
between two of the people in a particular group,

365
00:16:59,079 --> 00:17:01,321
is dictated by this equation.

366
00:17:02,082 --> 00:17:05,485
Now, at 23 people in a room,

367
00:17:05,725 --> 00:17:09,909
there's a 50% probability that two people have the same birthday.

368
00:17:10,570 --> 00:17:15,014
And at 70 people, there's a 99.9% probability.

369
00:17:15,075 --> 00:17:16,696
So I think we probably have two people

370
00:17:16,736 --> 00:17:18,198
that have the same birthday in the room today.

371
00:17:19,707 --> 00:17:21,987
Now, we've analyzed this for Keyforge,

372
00:17:22,448 --> 00:17:24,609
where D is the number of possible decks,

373
00:17:25,069 --> 00:17:26,869
and N is the number of decks we generate,

374
00:17:27,410 --> 00:17:29,370
we can get a table that looks something like this.

375
00:17:30,931 --> 00:17:34,973
So, on the left is the number of decks we generate,

376
00:17:35,773 --> 00:17:38,494
and in the center is the expected number of duplicate decks.

377
00:17:38,514 --> 00:17:43,296
So you can see that it takes us making 15 trillion decks

378
00:17:43,716 --> 00:17:46,817
before we can even expect to see one duplicate.

379
00:17:47,798 --> 00:17:47,918
And...

380
00:17:49,261 --> 00:17:50,542
I can tell you we haven't made that many.

381
00:17:52,343 --> 00:17:56,325
But just in case, we also do a uniqueness check.

382
00:17:56,526 --> 00:17:58,887
That checks a code against every other deck

383
00:17:58,907 --> 00:18:00,928
that's been generated just to ensure

384
00:18:00,988 --> 00:18:02,810
that no two decks have the same composition.

385
00:18:04,751 --> 00:18:06,132
So, there you go.

386
00:18:07,613 --> 00:18:09,474
Now, in terms of making card backs,

387
00:18:09,694 --> 00:18:11,395
we use a multi-part construction

388
00:18:11,495 --> 00:18:13,216
consisting of seven different pieces.

389
00:18:14,637 --> 00:18:17,059
Now, first is the body, the head,

390
00:18:17,699 --> 00:18:18,640
the left and right arm.

391
00:18:19,613 --> 00:18:22,654
the background, the symbol in the center of the card,

392
00:18:22,954 --> 00:18:23,535
and the color.

393
00:18:23,555 --> 00:18:26,136
Now these are all randomly generated

394
00:18:27,497 --> 00:18:29,298
because well, there's no other way

395
00:18:29,398 --> 00:18:31,859
to do this part of the card.

396
00:18:32,759 --> 00:18:35,501
But it's very interesting because the only way

397
00:18:35,561 --> 00:18:37,762
we can make this game is through digital printing.

398
00:18:39,362 --> 00:18:42,264
Traditional printing methods for a card game

399
00:18:42,304 --> 00:18:43,985
or even a board game don't apply here

400
00:18:44,745 --> 00:18:47,687
because typically board games use a process

401
00:18:47,707 --> 00:18:49,047
called black plate replacement.

402
00:18:49,492 --> 00:18:53,275
They print their cyan, magenta, and yellow layers first,

403
00:18:53,695 --> 00:18:55,357
and then they leave the black layer separate

404
00:18:55,937 --> 00:18:58,359
so that they can print in multiple different languages

405
00:18:59,079 --> 00:19:01,882
and they don't have to pay for more plates that way.

406
00:19:02,942 --> 00:19:05,745
Now, we have to use digital printing because Key Forge,

407
00:19:06,225 --> 00:19:08,246
well, we're only printing one of each deck.

408
00:19:08,266 --> 00:19:10,728
We're not trying to print a ton of the same deck.

409
00:19:11,489 --> 00:19:13,110
So, that's the only way we could go.

410
00:19:14,493 --> 00:19:18,095
Additionally, we do a uniqueness check for card backs

411
00:19:18,655 --> 00:19:21,216
by giving each and every piece of a card back

412
00:19:21,516 --> 00:19:22,996
a unique part of a code.

413
00:19:23,596 --> 00:19:25,017
When you line those codes all up,

414
00:19:25,337 --> 00:19:27,698
we can quickly check those numbers against one another

415
00:19:28,138 --> 00:19:30,479
and tell if we've used the same card back before.

416
00:19:33,140 --> 00:19:35,280
Now, another unique thing we have to do

417
00:19:35,740 --> 00:19:37,401
is figure out how decks get named.

418
00:19:38,601 --> 00:19:38,962
To do that,

419
00:19:39,570 --> 00:19:42,072
we have built a series of blueprints

420
00:19:42,513 --> 00:19:43,794
that look sort of like this,

421
00:19:43,954 --> 00:19:45,496
and by sort I mean exactly like this,

422
00:19:48,019 --> 00:19:50,501
that generates all of those different names

423
00:19:50,542 --> 00:19:51,282
that you might have seen.

424
00:19:52,664 --> 00:19:56,188
Now, those blueprints are filled out by word lists.

425
00:19:56,608 --> 00:19:58,230
We have 18 different ones.

426
00:19:58,510 --> 00:19:59,952
I'd tell you exactly what they were,

427
00:20:00,072 --> 00:20:01,513
but that'd be telling too much.

428
00:20:02,635 --> 00:20:04,877
But those word lists are pulled in

429
00:20:04,957 --> 00:20:08,580
to fill in those blueprints based on the different

430
00:20:09,881 --> 00:20:11,602
qualities of the cards in the deck.

431
00:20:12,002 --> 00:20:14,204
Whether it's a card that's more aggressive,

432
00:20:14,545 --> 00:20:17,667
deals damage, prevents your opponent from forging keys,

433
00:20:18,087 --> 00:20:21,831
all of those factor in to the eventual name of that archon.

434
00:20:22,331 --> 00:20:25,193
They qualify that deck for those different word lists.

435
00:20:25,974 --> 00:20:28,556
And once the deck has gone through

436
00:20:28,616 --> 00:20:30,418
and checked for all the word lists it qualifies for,

437
00:20:31,218 --> 00:20:32,999
Then, all the word lists get,

438
00:20:33,559 --> 00:20:35,019
the blueprints get filled out,

439
00:20:35,280 --> 00:20:36,940
and you can see we get stuff like

440
00:20:37,340 --> 00:20:38,961
Enforcer Wessel RepoFace,

