00:20:39,641 --> 00:20:41,402
the man who notably yearns for height,

442
00:20:41,642 --> 00:20:42,143
that's not me,

443
00:20:43,363 --> 00:20:44,864
and the king that surrounds porridge.

444
00:20:46,384 --> 00:20:49,406
And again, we take these and we do a uniqueness check

445
00:20:49,806 --> 00:20:51,947
to make sure we're not repeating ourselves

446
00:20:52,087 --> 00:20:54,388
and that each and every name is unique

447
00:20:54,568 --> 00:20:55,888
to the person that opens it.

448
00:20:57,762 --> 00:21:01,264
Now, so that gets past some of our mechanical hiccups

449
00:21:01,304 --> 00:21:02,564
we had to figure out and solve,

450
00:21:03,264 --> 00:21:05,205
but how did we test this game?

451
00:21:05,945 --> 00:21:07,986
I'm gonna talk about a little bit about our methodology

452
00:21:08,626 --> 00:21:10,887
and some of the questions we wanted to answer

453
00:21:11,047 --> 00:21:12,268
from our testing.

454
00:21:13,148 --> 00:21:14,769
So, in terms of methodology,

455
00:21:15,649 --> 00:21:18,170
we used an advanced specialized technique.

456
00:21:19,030 --> 00:21:20,071
We played it a lot.

457
00:21:21,871 --> 00:21:23,512
We used over 40 different groups,

458
00:21:23,592 --> 00:21:25,733
which is much more than typical for Key Forge.

459
00:21:26,347 --> 00:21:28,629
And we had over two years of testing,

460
00:21:28,709 --> 00:21:31,932
both internally, externally, and through our beta tests.

461
00:21:32,512 --> 00:21:33,833
This was an intense period,

462
00:21:34,053 --> 00:21:36,535
and we used a lot of different internal techniques

463
00:21:37,296 --> 00:21:40,638
to answer some of the most compelling questions to us

464
00:21:40,738 --> 00:21:43,000
about what makes Key Forge tick.

465
00:21:43,981 --> 00:21:47,323
Those focused on player skill versus deck strength.

466
00:21:48,286 --> 00:21:51,869
which is more influential to the success of a player.

467
00:21:52,689 --> 00:21:55,711
And to do that, we broke it down into three different tasks.

468
00:21:56,132 --> 00:21:57,813
The first two I'm gonna tell you about right now,

469
00:21:57,953 --> 00:22:01,936
and we'll get to the third in the third section of the talk.

470
00:22:02,496 --> 00:22:05,999
Now, how influential is deck composition?

471
00:22:06,799 --> 00:22:07,320
Task one.

472
00:22:08,741 --> 00:22:12,584
We created 60 different decks and divided those 60 decks

473
00:22:13,124 --> 00:22:14,765
into 10 groups of six.

474
00:22:15,646 --> 00:22:15,906
Then we.

475
00:22:18,011 --> 00:22:21,452
split those groups among our testing groups,

476
00:22:21,832 --> 00:22:23,913
doing this four times for our 40 different groups.

477
00:22:24,693 --> 00:22:26,953
Now, group A, or excuse me, group one,

478
00:22:27,033 --> 00:22:30,074
would receive decks from set A and B,

479
00:22:30,775 --> 00:22:33,135
two from B and C, and so on and so forth.

480
00:22:33,535 --> 00:22:34,896
This ensured that each deck

481
00:22:35,616 --> 00:22:37,776
existed in two different environments,

482
00:22:38,417 --> 00:22:39,257
and we could see how.

483
00:22:41,168 --> 00:22:43,468
its success in those different environments would vary.

484
00:22:43,969 --> 00:22:45,429
And this would give us an idea

485
00:22:45,669 --> 00:22:47,469
of how important that composition was,

486
00:22:47,549 --> 00:22:49,290
regardless of who was playing that deck.

487
00:22:50,370 --> 00:22:51,711
Now, when we did this,

488
00:22:51,791 --> 00:22:54,331
we had some really encouraging meta-implications.

489
00:22:54,371 --> 00:22:56,592
We had some decks that would dominate

490
00:22:56,952 --> 00:22:58,772
in both different groups they were in,

491
00:22:59,272 --> 00:23:00,953
some that would only dominate in one,

492
00:23:01,713 --> 00:23:03,153
and some that would dominate in neither.

493
00:23:04,294 --> 00:23:05,874
And to us, that felt like,

494
00:23:07,154 --> 00:23:10,055
man, there's a lot of possibilities for Key Forge.

495
00:23:10,415 --> 00:23:10,555
And...

496
00:23:11,176 --> 00:23:14,098
your local meta is going to be so interesting,

497
00:23:14,338 --> 00:23:16,040
and when you go to a different tournament,

498
00:23:16,720 --> 00:23:17,921
that can be completely different.

499
00:23:18,862 --> 00:23:21,124
That furthers the idea of discovery

500
00:23:21,184 --> 00:23:23,786
that we wanted to bring forth for the players,

501
00:23:24,226 --> 00:23:26,128
and it's always been at our core

502
00:23:26,208 --> 00:23:28,509
of what makes Key Forge so fun and interesting,

503
00:23:28,569 --> 00:23:29,970
is there's always something to discover.

504
00:23:31,932 --> 00:23:34,574
Now, task two, we wanted to figure out

505
00:23:35,375 --> 00:23:37,036
how important is player skill?

506
00:23:38,955 --> 00:23:41,296
So we had players take some of their favorite decks

507
00:23:41,336 --> 00:23:42,416
from the first part of testing

508
00:23:42,877 --> 00:23:45,377
and play a series of 20 matches with them.

509
00:23:46,218 --> 00:23:49,279
Now, after 10 matches, the players would switch decks.

510
00:23:50,199 --> 00:23:53,000
That way we could see whether it was the player skill

511
00:23:53,180 --> 00:23:55,040
or the deck strength that was really

512
00:23:55,381 --> 00:23:56,941
the culprit behind the success.

513
00:23:57,861 --> 00:24:00,742
And we often found that higher skilled players

514
00:24:00,882 --> 00:24:02,623
would in fact win more games in total

515
00:24:02,863 --> 00:24:04,323
regardless of what deck they were using.

516
00:24:05,108 --> 00:24:08,211
This is very encouraging because it meant that a player

517
00:24:08,351 --> 00:24:11,533
could, in fact, be more skilled at Keyforged than another,

518
00:24:12,233 --> 00:24:14,935
which with a game with such variety

519
00:24:14,995 --> 00:24:17,937
was really an important thing for us to find out.

520
00:24:20,059 --> 00:24:21,159
Now, last but not least,

521
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:23,401
let's talk about the user experience.

522
00:24:24,101 --> 00:24:25,422
How do you engage a player base

523
00:24:25,462 --> 00:24:28,084
with a game that's so bizarre and different?

524
00:24:28,184 --> 00:24:30,126
How do you make them feel like

525
00:24:30,166 --> 00:24:32,347
this is something they can rely on and invest in?

526
00:24:34,049 --> 00:24:38,470
We focused on ease of entry, flexibility in product,

527
00:24:39,190 --> 00:24:42,311
and making sure that players had tons of resources

528
00:24:42,691 --> 00:24:45,392
to aid their engagement, involvement in Key Forge.

529
00:24:47,212 --> 00:24:49,953
So first of all, ease of entry started

530
00:24:50,293 --> 00:24:52,393
from day one in design.

531
00:24:53,094 --> 00:24:55,774
We wanted to create a low barrier of entry

532
00:24:55,894 --> 00:24:57,915
just in how the game was put together.

533
00:24:59,175 --> 00:25:01,516
We did this by creating a streamlined series

534
00:25:01,556 --> 00:25:02,436
of decision points.

535
00:25:03,347 --> 00:25:07,289
Now this means that each turn, you're selecting an active house.

536
00:25:08,430 --> 00:25:10,811
This unclutters a turn.

537
00:25:11,071 --> 00:25:15,914
It makes it much more easy to process and go through because you're making your hardest

538
00:25:15,954 --> 00:25:17,275
decision right at the beginning.

539
00:25:17,975 --> 00:25:22,517
After you've made that hard decision, you're just left with a series of smaller, lighter

540
00:25:22,557 --> 00:25:25,219
decisions of what order are you going to do things in.

541
00:25:26,122 --> 00:25:28,965
This alleviates a lot of analysis paralysis

542
00:25:29,025 --> 00:25:31,527
that players face, because once they've made

543
00:25:31,567 --> 00:25:33,769
that hard decision, they just can go to the races.

544
00:25:35,050 --> 00:25:37,773
We also used a lot of warm language on cards,

545
00:25:38,353 --> 00:25:40,034
making it really easy to read

546
00:25:40,195 --> 00:25:41,676
and understand what effects did.

547
00:25:42,637 --> 00:25:44,518
This is important because players can often

548
00:25:44,538 --> 00:25:46,380
feel intimidated when they pick up a card

549
00:25:46,881 --> 00:25:48,542
and they have no idea how it functions.

550
00:25:49,363 --> 00:25:53,306
So, that was something we made sure to focus on very early.

551
00:25:54,323 --> 00:25:57,546
We also wanted to have simple card effects be at common.

552
00:25:57,826 --> 00:26:00,769
Now, common cards are the most frequently pulled into decks.

553
00:26:01,910 --> 00:26:04,672
And so by having more simple effects there,

554
00:26:05,133 --> 00:26:08,295
ones that were easy to grok, understand, and play with.

555
00:26:09,315 --> 00:26:12,977
we made sure that we kept the complexity of the game lower.

556
00:26:13,417 --> 00:26:17,159
In fact, the main philosophy behind rarity in Key Forge

557
00:26:17,419 --> 00:26:20,520
is focused not on power level, like in many other games,

558
00:26:21,001 --> 00:26:24,542
but on how complex the card is, how involved the card is

559
00:26:24,602 --> 00:26:27,224
for a player to use, and how much game knowledge is

560
00:26:27,264 --> 00:26:27,744
required.

561
00:26:28,244 --> 00:26:30,725
That way, as a player buys and continues

562
00:26:30,745 --> 00:26:34,287
their Key Forge career, they can learn those complexities

563
00:26:34,307 --> 00:26:35,428
a small bit at a time.

564
00:26:36,048 --> 00:26:38,069
Each time they play a game and encounter a new rare.

565
00:26:38,647 --> 00:26:40,769
then they'll learn something more about the game.

566
00:26:41,510 --> 00:26:44,013
We often have players, even now,

567
00:26:44,473 --> 00:26:46,816
discovering new rares that they've never seen before,

568
00:26:47,477 --> 00:26:50,019
which, again, is another point of discovery

569
00:26:50,300 --> 00:26:51,661
and fun for a player.

570
00:26:53,643 --> 00:26:56,967
We also wanted to have ease of entry in product design.

571
00:26:57,548 --> 00:26:59,370
We focused on a low cost for decks.

572
00:27:00,149 --> 00:27:01,830
early, early on in the process.

573
00:27:01,870 --> 00:27:04,572
We determined we wanted decks to be $9.95

574
00:27:05,112 --> 00:27:07,634
so that anyone could come in, pick up a deck of Keyforge,

575
00:27:07,674 --> 00:27:08,414
and just start playing.

576
00:27:09,955 --> 00:27:14,298
Now, also coupled with only needing a single purchase

577
00:27:14,338 --> 00:27:15,179
to play Keyforge.

578
00:27:15,940 --> 00:27:17,220
Sure, you can buy our starter set,

579
00:27:17,361 --> 00:27:19,582
but any player is just as well equipped

580
00:27:19,642 --> 00:27:22,124
by going to their store and picking up a single Archon deck.

581
00:27:23,405 --> 00:27:25,826
And I've often heard players say something like, hey,

582
00:27:26,327 --> 00:27:27,528
I'll get your first Keyforge.

583
00:27:28,891 --> 00:27:30,812
just implying that they'll walk into the store

584
00:27:30,892 --> 00:27:33,835
and both buy Archon decks and sit down and play a new game,

585
00:27:34,335 --> 00:27:37,317
having again that moment of discovery of this new deck.

586
00:27:38,598 --> 00:27:40,199
We also included quick start rules,

587
00:27:40,259 --> 00:27:42,101
both online and in the starter set,

588
00:27:42,661 --> 00:27:45,303
that allowed a player to get going in 10 to 15 minutes.

589
00:27:46,004 --> 00:27:48,926
That way there's no fumbling through a rule book

590
00:27:48,986 --> 00:27:49,826
for an hour or two.

591
00:27:50,027 --> 00:27:52,008
You can get going and start playing Key Forge

592
00:27:52,128 --> 00:27:52,949
as soon as possible.

593
00:27:55,110 --> 00:27:57,572
This flexibility in product is also reflected

594
00:27:57,712 --> 00:27:57,852
in our...

595
00:27:59,861 --> 00:28:02,162
enormous pile of formats, of which I'll share

596
00:28:02,202 --> 00:28:03,443
just a few with you guys today.

597
00:28:05,304 --> 00:28:08,085
Formats meaning how a player plays the game

598
00:28:09,085 --> 00:28:11,627
and what structure is a tournament set up in.

599
00:28:12,207 --> 00:28:15,688
So, sealed, meaning that you show up to your game store,

600
00:28:15,889 --> 00:28:18,170
you buy a single Archon deck, you open it up,

601
00:28:18,510 --> 00:28:19,670
and then you play a tournament with it.

602
00:28:20,691 --> 00:28:24,292
This fosters so many different interesting discovery moments

603
00:28:24,413 --> 00:28:26,053
as you're learning how your deck plays,

604
00:28:26,774 --> 00:28:28,134
along with everyone else that's learning

605
00:28:28,174 --> 00:28:28,895
how their deck plays.

606
00:28:30,660 --> 00:28:33,043
Archon format is our bring your best deck

607
00:28:33,544 --> 00:28:34,946
and play a tournament with it format.

608
00:28:35,487 --> 00:28:37,730
It's our most bread and butter vanilla format,

609
00:28:38,672 --> 00:28:43,419
which more TCG players will be at ease with,

610
00:28:44,260 --> 00:28:45,822
and will be able to understand.

611
00:28:47,302 --> 00:28:49,943
Adaptive is one of our more interesting formats

612
00:28:50,463 --> 00:28:53,124
in which players will bring their decks,

613
00:28:53,344 --> 00:28:54,264
they'll play a game with them,

614
00:28:54,824 --> 00:28:57,205
and then they'll switch decks with their opponent,

615
00:28:57,745 --> 00:28:58,785
playing a second game.

616
00:28:59,446 --> 00:29:03,307
Then, if each player has won one game at that point,

617
00:29:04,007 --> 00:29:05,927
players will then bid chains for the deck

618
00:29:05,967 --> 00:29:06,908
that won both games.

619
00:29:09,788 --> 00:29:11,509
We'll get to what chains are in a minute, excuse me.

620
00:29:12,787 --> 00:29:13,948
We also have survival format,

621
00:29:14,268 --> 00:29:15,990
in which players will bring multiple decks,

622
00:29:16,770 --> 00:29:18,612
and each time they lose with one of those decks,

623
00:29:19,032 --> 00:29:20,233
that deck is out of the tournament.

624
00:29:20,774 --> 00:29:22,555
The last player with decks left wins.

625
00:29:24,677 --> 00:29:27,999
Then, reversal, in which players bring a deck

626
00:29:28,380 --> 00:29:31,102
they feel like they can beat, they know how to beat.

627
00:29:31,923 --> 00:29:33,604
And, at the beginning of each tournament round,

628
00:29:33,844 --> 00:29:35,245
they'll switch decks with their opponent,

629
00:29:35,345 --> 00:29:38,168
who has also brought a deck they feel like they can beat.

630
00:29:38,984 --> 00:29:40,605
and you'll play against the same deck

631
00:29:40,966 --> 00:29:42,307
every single round of the tournament

632
00:29:42,888 --> 00:29:46,472
instead of playing and play with a new deck every round,

633
00:29:47,893 --> 00:29:50,296
which has been a really fun and exciting format

634
00:29:50,476 --> 00:29:52,999
that has added a lot of value to decks

635
00:29:53,059 --> 00:29:56,503
that players may not feel like are up to par

636
00:29:56,543 --> 00:29:57,544
with some of their other decks,

637
00:29:57,904 --> 00:30:01,068
meaning that more of your purchases are in fact valuable.

638
00:30:03,118 --> 00:30:07,599
So, I mentioned I'd talk about chains and task three earlier, and here they are.

639
00:30:08,419 --> 00:30:12,080
Chains are a handicapping mechanic we've added to Keyforge.

640
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:16,701
And it's really important because it allows players to even the odds.

641
00:30:17,241 --> 00:30:22,443
No matter what decks that you open, you can always use chains to bring those decks into

642
00:30:22,503 --> 00:30:23,383
parity with one another.

643
00:30:23,983 --> 00:30:28,304
So even if you only want to go out and buy two decks and play with a friend.

644
00:30:29,386 --> 00:30:30,886
you'll be able to play those two decks

645
00:30:30,946 --> 00:30:31,927
no matter how good they are.

646
00:30:32,747 --> 00:30:36,988
Chains are a mechanic that restrict the number of cards

647
00:30:37,008 --> 00:30:38,589
you're allowed to draw at the end of your turn,

648
00:30:39,189 --> 00:30:41,389
slowing down decks that earn more of them

649
00:30:42,210 --> 00:30:44,670
and giving decks that don't have chains

650
00:30:44,730 --> 00:30:45,851
a better chance against them.

651
00:30:46,531 --> 00:30:48,971
There's also powerful cards in the game

652
00:30:49,392 --> 00:30:50,932
that cause a player to gain chains,

653
00:30:51,552 --> 00:30:53,633
meaning that if you push too hard,

654
00:30:54,073 --> 00:30:55,373
you may be causing yourself.

655
00:30:56,931 --> 00:30:57,931
the game because of it.

656
00:30:59,552 --> 00:31:02,213
Additionally, our weekly tournament type

657
00:31:02,373 --> 00:31:03,754
is called a chain-bound tournament.

658
00:31:04,314 --> 00:31:07,676
This lets us use chains to help regulate a local metagame.

659
00:31:08,877 --> 00:31:10,498
Every week that a player comes and plays,

660
00:31:10,618 --> 00:31:13,559
depending on how successful they are during that week,

661
00:31:14,040 --> 00:31:15,921
their chains are added to their deck,

662
00:31:16,681 --> 00:31:19,202
which will then be there in subsequent weeks of the tournament.

663
00:31:20,243 --> 00:31:21,123
So, as...

664
00:31:22,370 --> 00:31:25,091
The weeks go on, the meta at the local level

665
00:31:25,191 --> 00:31:26,251
will be changed by this.

666
00:31:26,751 --> 00:31:29,832
Players that will rank up their decks in chains

667
00:31:30,112 --> 00:31:32,133
will then have to either continue playing

668
00:31:32,193 --> 00:31:35,713
with a handicapped deck or switch to a different deck.

669
00:31:36,073 --> 00:31:38,474
Meaning that every week you come to play at Key Forge

670
00:31:39,054 --> 00:31:40,594
is a different, different story,

671
00:31:40,695 --> 00:31:42,295
giving you another moment of discovery.

672
00:31:44,355 --> 00:31:47,356
We also wanted to give tons of different player resources.

673
00:31:47,876 --> 00:31:50,957
And these all focused on our Master Vault app and website.

674
00:31:52,017 --> 00:31:52,137
Yeah.

675
00:31:52,974 --> 00:31:56,262
Master Vault app and website provides a reference hub for players.

676
00:31:56,562 --> 00:31:58,888
A place to go and find all things Keyforge.

677
00:31:59,721 --> 00:32:02,523
There we track the decks, how many chains they have,

678
00:32:03,164 --> 00:32:05,705
and the number of wins and losses they've had in tournament play.

679
00:32:06,346 --> 00:32:09,869
It also shows off a mechanic we call the power level of the deck.

680
00:32:10,549 --> 00:32:12,851
Now this ensures that decks that are doing well

681
00:32:13,511 --> 00:32:14,952
are increasing in power levels,

682
00:32:15,633 --> 00:32:19,636
and each different type of tournament or experience we have for players

683
00:32:19,996 --> 00:32:21,837
has a power level regulation

684
00:32:22,058 --> 00:32:26,141
in which you can't play decks above a certain power level in that.

685
00:32:26,641 --> 00:32:26,981
That means...

686
00:32:27,787 --> 00:32:30,068
For example, we just had a vault tour this last weekend.

687
00:32:30,888 --> 00:32:32,789
It's our premium play experience.

688
00:32:33,709 --> 00:32:36,470
Each deck that won the vault tour is now power level eight,

689
00:32:37,410 --> 00:32:39,791
meaning that those decks can't compete

690
00:32:39,911 --> 00:32:41,872
at those weekly chain-bound tournaments anymore

691
00:32:42,472 --> 00:32:43,633
because those decks have proven

692
00:32:43,673 --> 00:32:44,993
exactly how powerful they are.

693
00:32:45,593 --> 00:32:47,874
And we can let the chain-bound tournaments

694
00:32:47,934 --> 00:32:49,635
that those decks would normally participate in

695
00:32:49,975 --> 00:32:50,875
evolve and change.

696
00:32:52,476 --> 00:32:55,337
The Master Vault website also allows players

697
00:32:55,357 --> 00:32:56,957
to find stores with Key Forge events.

698
00:32:57,860 --> 00:33:00,282
I'm also happy to say that that number of decks registered

699
00:33:00,302 --> 00:33:01,142
you see down in the corner,

700
00:33:01,563 --> 00:33:04,726
passed 700,000 just a couple days ago.

701
00:33:08,228 --> 00:33:09,970
But, what's next for Keyforge?

702
00:33:10,791 --> 00:33:14,474
And that is our first new set called Age of Ascension,

703
00:33:14,754 --> 00:33:16,415
just announced about a month ago.

704
00:33:17,877 --> 00:33:21,320
Now, Age of Ascension is gonna add 204 new cards

705
00:33:21,440 --> 00:33:22,641
to the Keyforge environment.

706
00:33:24,090 --> 00:33:26,794
It's also gonna bring along 166 cards

707
00:33:26,914 --> 00:33:28,757
from the first set, Call of the Archons.

708
00:33:29,418 --> 00:33:31,501
Now this is really intriguing and interesting

709
00:33:32,002 --> 00:33:33,705
because most other TCGs.

710
00:33:34,437 --> 00:33:35,758
wouldn't be able to do something like this

711
00:33:35,878 --> 00:33:37,498
because players already have those cards.

712
00:33:37,879 --> 00:33:39,159
They wouldn't want more of them.

713
00:33:39,659 --> 00:33:43,801
But in Key Forge, those 166 cards are given new life,

714
00:33:44,481 --> 00:33:46,602
a new experience because they're alongside

715
00:33:47,342 --> 00:33:48,303
204 completely new cards.

716
00:33:48,743 --> 00:33:52,524
The value of those 166 cards changes inherently

717
00:33:52,964 --> 00:33:54,705
based on the other cards that are in your deck.

718
00:33:55,105 --> 00:33:56,686
So you'll see powerful favorites,

719
00:33:57,186 --> 00:33:59,507
but they're gonna be in a completely new context

720
00:33:59,887 --> 00:34:03,308
allowing you to discover them all over again.

721
00:34:05,747 --> 00:34:09,191
Additionally, we also have a legacy card mechanic.

722
00:34:10,032 --> 00:34:13,155
Now, legacy cards are rare cards

723
00:34:13,696 --> 00:34:15,298
that are from previous sets,

724
00:34:15,899 --> 00:34:17,661
and they're pulled into the current set.

725
00:34:18,585 --> 00:34:19,966
Again, only very rarely.

726
00:34:20,567 --> 00:34:23,289
This means that every single card that is in

727
00:34:23,569 --> 00:34:25,611
Call of the Archons can be found

728
00:34:25,991 --> 00:34:27,152
in an Age of Ascension deck.

729
00:34:27,632 --> 00:34:29,614
And when a player finds one of those legacy cards,

730
00:34:29,994 --> 00:34:32,436
it acts as another cool moment of discovery.

731
00:34:32,656 --> 00:34:33,897
Something new, something different,

732
00:34:34,278 --> 00:34:35,479
something they weren't expecting.

733
00:34:36,039 --> 00:34:37,840
And so, whenever you open a Key Forge deck,

734
00:34:37,900 --> 00:34:39,202
you never know what you're gonna get.

735
00:34:40,176 --> 00:34:42,436
We've also introduced a bunch of new mechanics

736
00:34:42,916 --> 00:34:45,377
that you can check out the Fantasy Flight Games website

737
00:34:45,517 --> 00:34:47,917
to see what we've been premiering so far.

738
00:34:48,578 --> 00:34:50,758
It should release in the second quarter of this year

739
00:34:50,958 --> 00:34:52,558
and we're incredibly excited.

740
00:34:53,899 --> 00:34:55,599
But that's it for me today.

741
00:34:56,619 --> 00:34:57,979
We have time for some questions now.

742
00:34:58,500 --> 00:35:00,880
There is a microphone stand right in the center of the room

743
00:35:01,080 --> 00:35:02,940
so if you have any questions you'd like to ask,

744
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:06,201
please line up there and we'll get to it.

745
00:35:09,472 --> 00:35:11,554
Oh, and please say your name and where you're from.

746
00:35:13,136 --> 00:35:13,877
Thank you very much.

747
00:35:19,022 --> 00:35:20,003
Hello, my name is Jay.

748
00:35:20,124 --> 00:35:21,345
I'm from Southern California.

749
00:35:21,685 --> 00:35:21,986
Hey, Jay.

750
00:35:23,700 --> 00:35:24,420
Can I call you Quicksilve?

751
00:35:24,881 --> 00:35:25,801
Yeah, sure, go for it.

752
00:35:26,582 --> 00:35:28,043
There was a meme not too long ago

753
00:35:28,764 --> 00:35:30,565
involving Quicksilve, the card,

754
00:35:30,585 --> 00:35:34,028
and someone saying they wanted a person just like Quicksilve

755
00:35:34,068 --> 00:35:36,890
and then underneath was like, I am that person.

756
00:35:37,250 --> 00:35:37,550
Yeah.

757
00:35:38,091 --> 00:35:39,072
Did that actually happen?

758
00:35:39,772 --> 00:35:40,473
No, no, no.

